DOCUMENT();

loadMacros(
  "PGstandard.pl",
  "MathObjects.pl",
  "PGML.pl",
  "contextFraction.pl",
  "PGcourse.pl"
);

##############################################

Context("LimitedFraction");
Context()->flags->set(requirePureFractions=>1);
Context()->flags->set(showMixedNumbers=>0);

$integer = non_zero_random(-5,5,1);

$den2 = random(2,10,1);
do {$num2 = random(1,$den2-1,1);} until (gcd($num2,$den2)==1);
$frac2 = Fraction($num2,$den2);

$ans = ($integer + $frac2)->reduce;
@temp = $ans->value;
$numAns = $temp[0];
$denAns = $temp[1];

$neg="";
if ($numAns<0) {
   $neg="-";
   $numAns = -$numAns;
}

##############################################

TEXT(beginproblem());

BEGIN_PGML

Add these together: [`` [$integer] + \frac{[$num2]}{[$den2]}``]

When needed, use an improper fraction in your answer. Don't use a mixed number.

    [___________]{$ans} 

END_PGML

##############################################

$num1 = $integer * $den2;

BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION

When doing arithmetic with fractions, it is helpful to rewrite any integers as fractions:

    [`` [$integer] = \frac{[$integer]}{1} ``]

Next, to add two fractions, we need to find a common denominator. In this case, it is simply the second denominator [`[$den2]`]. We will rewrite the first fraction:

    [`` \begin{aligned}\frac{[$integer]}{1} &= \frac{[$integer] \cdot [$den2]}{1 \cdot [$den2]}\\ &= \frac{[$num1]}{[$den2]} \end{aligned}``]

Finally, we add the numerators and keep the denominator unchanged. The whole process is:

    [``
\begin{aligned}
   [$integer] + \frac{[$num2]}{[$den2]}
        &= \frac{[$num1]}{[$den2]} + \frac{[$num2]}{[$den2]} \\
        &= \frac{[$num1] + [$num2]}{[$den2]} \\
        &= [$neg]\frac{[$numAns]}{[$denAns]}
\end{aligned}
    ``]

The answer to this question is  [` [$ans]`].

END_PGML_SOLUTION

